<document>
	<title>Failure of bronchopulmonary lavage in cystic fibrosis.</title>

	<author>Braunstein-M-S.</author>
	<author>Fleegler-B.</author>

	<source>Chest. 1974 Jul. 66(1). P 96-9.</source>

	<abstract>In an attempt to retard deterioration of pulmonary function, a
   young man with cystic fibrosis underwent broncho-pulmonary
   lavage of an entire lung.  In spite of theoretical advantages, the
   lavage produced an acute deterioration in the patient&apos;s clinical and
   physiologic status, from which he had not recovered one month later.
   We conclude that bronchopulmonary lavage in cystic fibrosis may be
   hazardous and should be reserved for those cases in which
   conventional methods of improving tracheobronchial clearance have
   failed.</abstract>

